tockhausen, and “Allover” Painting -- tPart Seven: Criticism and the Critic -- t15 Rosen’s Modernist Haydn -- t16 Facile Metaphors, Hidden Gaps, Short Circuits: Should We Adore Adorno? -- t17 The Music of a Classical Style -- t18 Montaigne hors de son propos -- tThree Tributes -- tUne culture vraiment intimidante -- tCharles Rosen for His Eightieth Birthday -- tCharles Rosen: A Personal Appreciation by a Contemporary -- tAppendices -- tAppendix 1: A Discography of the Recordings of Charles Rosen -- tAppendix 2: A Bibliography of the Writings of Charles Rosen -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMasterful essays honoring the great pianist and critic Charles Rosen, on masterpieces from Bach and Beethoven to Chopin, Verdi, and Stockhausen.Charles Rosen, the pianist and man of letters, is perhaps the single most influential writer on music of the past half-century. While Rosen's vast range as a writer and performer is encyclopedic, it has focused particularly on theliving "canonical" repertory extending from Bach to Boulez. Inspired in its liveliness and variety of critical approaches by Charles Rosen's challenging work, Variations on the Canon offers original essays by some of the world's most eminent musical scholars. Contributors address such issues as style and compositional technique, genre, influence and modeling, and reception history; develop insights afforded by close examination of compositional sketches; and consider what language and metaphors might most meaningfully convey insights into music. However diverse the modes of inquiry, each essay sheds new light on the works of those composers posterity has deemed central to the modern Western musical tradition. Contributors: Pierre Boulez, Scott Burnham, Elliott Carter, Robert Curry, Walter Frisch, David Gable, Philip Gossett, Jeffrey Kallberg, Joseph Kerman, Richard Kramer, William Kinderman, Lewis Lockwood, Sir Charles Mackerras, Robert L. Marshall, Robert P. Morgan, Charles Rosen, Julian Rushton, David Schulenberg, László Somfai, Leo Treitler, James Webster, and Robert Winter. Robert Curry is principalof the Conservatorium High School and honorary senior lecturer in the Centre for Medieval Studies, University of Sydney; David Gable is Assistant Professor of Music at Clark-Atlanta University; Robert L. Marshall is Louis, Frances, and Jeffrey Sachar Professor Emeritus of Music at Brandeis University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aClassical Music.  aMusic Analysis.  aMusic History.  aMusic Interpretation.  aMusicology.1 aBoulez, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnham, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Elliott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurry, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurry, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrisch, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGable, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGable, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGossett, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKallberg, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerman, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinderman, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLockw